Pneumonia Detection using CNN and Object Detection¶

Capstone project¶

This notebook Goal is to look at given set of chest X-Ray images and create a model to classify whether a patient have Lung Opacity or not. If there is a lung opacity, provide marking. There is a third class "No lung opacity/Not normal" which is nothing but there is no peunomonia but the lung doesnot look normal too. We can optionally have marking for the third class.

We have three milesone¶

Milestone 1:¶

Create a model to do classification of given patient dicom(xray) images to either they have Pneumonia or normal or no pneumonia/not normal.

Milestone 2:¶

Fine tune model, Apply Transfer learning and Perform object detection

Milestone 3:¶

Deploy model with UI

------------------------------ Milestone 1 ------------------------------¶

import os
import pydicom as dicom
import skimage.transform as st
import tensorflow as tf
import tensorflow_io as tfio

image_directory = zip_directory + "/train_images/stage_2_train_images"
total_number_of_files = 0
image_df = pd.DataFrame(columns=['image_file_name', 'path', 'actual_image', 'height', 'width'])
# Iterate directory
i = 0
for file in os.listdir(image_directory):
    # check if current path is a file
    if os.path.isfile(os.path.join(image_directory, file)):
        total_number_of_files += 1
        dicom_image = dicom.dcmread(os.path.join(image_directory, file))
        image_df.loc[i, 'path'] = os.path.join(image_directory, file)
        image_df.loc[i, 'image_file_name'] = file
        image_df.loc[i, 'actual_image'] = np.array((st.resize(dicom_image.pixel_array, (32, 32), anti_aliasing=True))/255)                
        image_df.loc[i, 'height'] = dicom_image.Columns
        image_df.loc[i, 'width'] = dicom_image.Rows
        i+=1
print(f"We have {total_number_of_files} total number of image files");

In [42]:
# For validation of model result have test:train:validation split
# It will help understand model accuracy
from sklearn.model_selection import train_test_split

def train_test_val_split(X,Y):
    train_ratio = 0.75
    validation_ratio = 0.10
    test_ratio = 0.15
    
    x_train, x_test, y_train, y_test = train_test_split(X, Y, test_size=1 - train_ratio)
    x_val, x_test, y_val, y_test = train_test_split(x_test, y_test, test_size=test_ratio/(test_ratio + validation_ratio))
    print(f"{x_train.shape} is x_train shape, {x_test.shape} x_test shape, {x_val.shape} x_val shape, {y_train.shape} is y_train shape, {y_test.shape} y_test shape, {y_val.shape} y_val shape")
    return x_train, x_test, x_val, y_train, y_test, y_val

Step - 6.3 Build basic CNN model with three convulution layer with sofmax for multi- classification¶

In [47]:
from tensorflow.keras.models import Sequential
from tensorflow.keras.layers import InputLayer,Activation, Conv2D, Dropout, Dense, Flatten, BatchNormalization, MaxPool2D, GlobalMaxPool2D
from tensorflow.keras import optimizers
from tensorflow.keras.callbacks import EarlyStopping
In [48]:
def get_model():
    model = Sequential()
    
    model.add(InputLayer(input_shape = (32,32,3,)))
    model.add(Conv2D(64, kernel_size=(3,3), activation='relu'))
    model.add(BatchNormalization())
    
    model.add(Conv2D(64, kernel_size=(3,3), activation='relu'))
    model.add(BatchNormalization())
    model.add(Conv2D(128, kernel_size=(3,3), activation='relu'))
    
    model.add(Dense(128, activation='relu'))
    model.add(Dense(64, activation='relu'))
    model.add(BatchNormalization())
    model.add(Flatten())
    
    model.add(Dense(3, activation='softmax'))
    return model

# Few reference material studied for this. The Grid Search Model is something not suitable for PC/laptop environment as 
# it tends to take lot of time which puts the system in high utilization. The summar time adds up to the heat and power cut 
# which makes the system shutdown while running. The best place to run all these is Cloud. Followinv code was written 
# kept all these bad experience in mind. Hence the early stopping callback was set ever where to 3.
#
# https://machinelearningmastery.com/understand-the-dynamics-of-learning-rate-on-deep-learning-neural-networks/#:~:text=Stochastic%20Gradient%20Descent,-Keras%20provides%20the&text=The%20default%20learning%20rate%20is,momentum%20is%20used%20by%20default.&text=The%20learning%20rate%20can%20be,via%20the%20%E2%80%9Cmomentum%E2%80%9D%20argument.&text=The%20class%20also%20supports%20learning,via%20the%20%E2%80%9Cdecay%E2%80%9D%20argument.
# https://machinelearningmastery.com/grid-search-hyperparameters-deep-learning-models-python-keras/

Step - 1.2.1: Find best LR and Momentum¶

In [111]:
# fit a model and plot learning curve with different learning rate.
# The learning rate is something we choose in randomly for analysis
# Keras default for SGD is 0.001
def fit_model_find_lr(trainX, trainy, testX, testy, lrate):
    optimizer = optimizers.SGD(learning_rate=lrate) 
    model3.compile(loss = 'sparse_categorical_crossentropy', optimizer=optimizer, metrics=['accuracy'])
    earlyStoppingCallback = EarlyStopping(monitor='val_loss', patience=5)
    model3_history = model3.fit(X_train, y_train, epochs = 10, batch_size=100,
                        validation_data=(X_test, y_test), callbacks=[earlyStoppingCallback], verbose=0)
    # plot learning curves
    plt.plot(model3_history.history['accuracy'], label='train')
    plt.plot(model3_history.history['val_accuracy'], label='test')
    plt.title('lrate='+str(lrate), pad=-50)
    
learning_rates = [0.00001, 0.0001, 0.1]
for i in tqdm(range(len(learning_rates))):
    plot_no = 420 + (i+1)
    plt.subplot(plot_no)
    plt.tight_layout()
    fit_model_find_lr(X_train, y_train, X_test, y_test, learning_rates[i])
    
# show learning curves
plt.show()

100%|| 3/3 [6:09:30<00:00, 7390.12s/it]
With learning rate 0.1 we seem to be hitting some thing above 60% accuracy. Earlier with default learing rate we have had 65% accuracy on test data. So we will get some good accuracy when we have learning rate lr > 0.001 and < 0.1. We should try something in between. Due to resource limitation on personal computer we will stick with 0.001 which is default LR for SGD.¶
In [113]:
# fit a model and plot learning curve
def fit_model_find_momentum(trainX, trainy, testX, testy, lrate, mtum):
    optimizer = optimizers.SGD(learning_rate=lrate, momentum=mtum) 
    model3.compile(loss = 'sparse_categorical_crossentropy', optimizer=optimizer, metrics=['accuracy'])
    earlyStoppingCallback = EarlyStopping(monitor='val_loss', patience=3)
    model3_history = model3.fit(X_train, y_train, epochs = 10, batch_size=BATCH_SIZE,
                        validation_data=(X_test, y_test), callbacks=[earlyStoppingCallback])
    # plot learning curves
    plt.plot(model3_history.history['accuracy'], label='train')
    plt.plot(model3_history.history['val_accuracy'], label='test')
    plt.title('momentum='+str(mtum), pad=-50)
    
momentums = [0.5, 0.9, 0.99]
for i in tqdm(range(len(momentums))):
    plot_no = 420 + (i+1)
    plt.subplot(plot_no)
    fit_model_find_momentum(X_train, y_train, X_test, y_test, , momentums[i])

                                weights='imagenet')

model_dense.add(Dropout(.5))
model_dense.add(BatchNormalization())
model_dense.add(Dense(256,activation=('relu')))
model_dense.add(Dropout(.3))

model_dense.add(Dense(128,activation=('relu'))) 
model_dense.add(Dropout(.3))
model_dense.add(Dense(128,activation=('relu')))
model_dense.add(Dropout(.3))

# Output layer
model_dense.add(Dense(3,activation=('softmax'))) 

#Check final model summary
model_dense.summary()

Model_1 is something that we carried from milestone one with very limited number of hidden layer which was giving above 50% accuracy.¶

Model_2 is an updated version of model_1 which was giving 66% accuracy with SDG Optimizer.¶

Model_3 is where we kept model_2 as base and tried to find best learning rate and momentum further to optimize. The initial plan was to get the best value with increased accuracy and then try more number of epoch. The learning rate we used was [0.00001, 0.0001, 0.1] and momentum we tried was [0.5, 0.9, 0.99]. We did not get a best value though learning rate 0.1 was showing some improvement.¶

Model_4 is updated version of model_2 with Adam optimizer¶

We then tried some transfer learning technique using Keras VGG, RestNET, DenseNet and MoileNet¶

If you see the report - the customized DesnNet was showing good improvement from base model however it is still under 60% accuracy. We should be able to optimize this further with more number of retrying using Keras Tuner kind of packages.¶

I have stopped with this assuming Model_2 as Best Model as it took more than a week time to run in my laptop with lots of hiccups here and there.¶

def convert_dicom_to_jpg(dicom_image_path, jpg_folder):
    ds = dicom.dcmread(dicom_image_path)
    pixel_array_numpy = ds.pixel_array
    jpg_image = dicom_image_path.replace('.dcm', '.jpg')
    cv2.imwrite(os.path.join(jpg_folder, jpg_image), pixel_array_numpy)

In [35]:
def calculate_iou(bb_1, bb_2):
    '''
  Now we are initialising the function to calculate IOU (Intersection Over Union) 
  of the ground truth box from the box computed by selective search.
  To divide the generated ROIs, for example, we can use a metric called IoU. 
  Its defined as the intersection area divided by area of the union of a predicted 
  bounding box and ground-truth box.
  '''
    assert bb_1['x1'] < bb_1['x2']    # The assert keyword lets you test if a condition in your code returns True, 
    assert bb_1['y1'] < bb_1['y2']    # if not, the program will raise an AssertionError.
    assert bb_2['x1'] < bb_2['x2']
    assert bb_2['y1'] < bb_2['y2']

    x_left = max(bb_1['x1'], bb_2['x1'])
    y_top = max(bb_1['y1'], bb_2['y1'])
    x_right = min(bb_1['x2'], bb_2['x2'])
    y_bottom = min(bb_1['y2'], bb_2['y2'])

    if x_right < x_left or y_bottom < y_top:
        return 0.0

    intersection = (x_right - x_left) * (y_bottom - y_top)

    bb_1_area = (bb_1['x2'] - bb_1['x1']) * (bb_1['y2'] - bb_1['y1'])
    bb_2_area = (bb_2['x2'] - bb_2['x1']) * (bb_2['y2'] - bb_2['y1'])

    iou_value = intersection / float(bb_1_area + bb_2_area - intersection)
    assert iou_value >= 0.0
    assert iou_value <= 1.0
    return iou_value

import torch
import torchvision.ops.boxes as bops

count = 0
for i, row in data.iterrows():
    if (row['Target'] == 0):
        continue
    try:
        #coordinates=[]
        patientId = row['patientId'] + ".jpg"
        image = cv2.imread(os.path.join(TRAIN_IMAGE_FOLDER,patientId))
        #coordinates.append({"x1":row['x'],"x2":row['y'],"y1":row['width_y'],"y2":row['height_y']})
        coordinates = [[row['x'],row['y'],row['width_y'],row['height_y']]]
        #print(coordinates)
        ss_object.setBaseImage(image)
        ss_object.switchToSelectiveSearchFast()
        ss_results = ss_object.process()
        print(ss_results.size)
        image_new = image.copy()
        min_positive_samples = 0
        min_negative_samples = 0
        print(i, patientId)
        if (count >= 2):
            break
        count += 1
        for region,ss_coordinate in enumerate(ss_results):
            if region < ss_results.size :
                box1 = torch.tensor(coordinates, dtype=torch.float)
                box2 = torch.tensor([np.array(ss_coordinate)], dtype=torch.float)
                iou = bops.box_iou(box1, box2)
                print(f"{box1} {box2} {iou}")
                if min_positive_samples < 30:
                    if iou > 0.70:
                        mobile_obj_img = image_new[y:y+h,x:x+w]
                        resized_image = cv2.resize(mobile_obj_img, (224,224), interpolation = cv2.INTER_AREA)
                        train_data.append(resized_image)
                        train_labels_data.append(1)
                        min_positive_samples += 1               
                if min_negative_samples < 30:
                    if iou < 0.3:
                        mobile_obj_img = image_new[y:y+h,x:x+w]
                        resized_image = cv2.resize(mobile_obj_img, (224,224), interpolation = cv2.INTER_AREA)
                        train_data.append(resized_image)
                        train_labels_data.append(0)
                        min_negative_samples += 1                
    except Exception as e:
        print(f"Exception {repr(e)}")
        continue
